Jurisdiction & Court Selection.answer:
Under s14 LA 1980, the date of knowledge is the date on which the claimant first had knowledge of all of the following:
(1) That the injury was significant (sufficiently serious to justify proceedings against a defendant who does not dispute liability and is able to satisfy judgment);
(2) That the injury was attributable in whole or in part to the act or omission alleged to constitute negligence, nuisance, or breach of duty;
(3) The identity of the defendant;
(4) If the act or omission was by someone other than the defendant, the identity of that person and the additional facts supporting the claim.

The claimant is fixed with constructive knowledge — what they ought reasonably to have known, including with the benefit of expert advice they should reasonably have sought (s14(3) LA 1980).

⚠️ Knowledge of legal rights is not required — only knowledge of the factual ingredients. A claimant who knows the facts but not that they have a legal claim cannot postpone the limitation period.

Track Allocation.answer:
The three tracks are (CPR 26):
(1) Small claims track: claims of £10,000 or less (£1,000 or less for personal injury and housing disrepair claims);
(2) Fast track: claims over £10,000 and up to £25,000 that can be tried within one day (PI claims: over £1,000 and up to £25,000);
(3) Multi-track: claims over £25,000, or lower-value claims that are too complex for the fast track.

Financial value is the primary but not determinative factor — the court considers all the circumstances of the case (CPR 26.8).

⚠️ Recommend verifying the PI small claims threshold (£1,000) against the current CPR — this figure has been subject to proposed reform.

Fast track standard directions typically provide for (CPR 28):
(1) Standard disclosure: within 4 weeks;
(2) Exchange of witness statements: within 10 weeks;
(3) Expert evidence (if permitted): single joint expert preferred; exchange of reports within 14 weeks;
(4) Listing questionnaire (pre-trial checklist): within 20 weeks;
(5) Trial: within 30 weeks of directions being given.

Trial is limited to one day. Fixed trial advocacy costs apply, linked to the amount recovered. The court will usually not permit departure from fixed trial costs unless there are exceptional circumstances.

On the multi-track (CPR 29), the court actively manages proceedings using:
(1) Case management conferences (CMCs): the court reviews progress, resolves disputes about directions, and gives tailored directions;
(2) Pre-trial reviews (PTRs): closer to trial to ensure the case is ready;
(3) Costs budgeting: parties must file and exchange Precedent H budgets, approved at a costs and case management conference (CCMC);
(4) Tailored directions: not standardised — the court designs a timetable specific to the issues in the case.

Multi-track directions vary significantly by case complexity. The Commercial Court and Chancery Division may use their own practice directions.

Freezing Injunctions.answer:
A freezing injunction (formerly Mareva injunction) prevents a defendant from disposing of or dealing with assets to frustrate a judgment. Jurisdiction is under s37 Senior Courts Act 1981. To obtain one, the applicant must show:
(1) A good arguable case on the merits — higher than the 'serious question' test for ordinary interim injunctions;
(2) The defendant has assets within the jurisdiction (domestic order), or for a worldwide freezing order, additional requirements apply;
(3) There is a real risk that the defendant will dissipate assets before judgment.

Applications are made without notice. The applicant gives a cross-undertaking in damages. Standard form orders include a living expenses carve-out and allow the defendant to continue ordinary business dealings.

⚠️ A freezing injunction does not give the claimant security or priority over other creditors — it merely prevents dissipation. This is a key limit students overlook.

Search Orders.answer:
A search order (formerly Anton Piller order, CPR 25.1(1)(h)) requires the respondent to permit entry to premises to search for, inspect, and seize specified documents or property. The court will only grant one where:
(1) The applicant has an extremely strong prima facie case;
(2) The potential or actual damage is very serious;
(3) There is clear evidence that the respondent has relevant items and would destroy or conceal them if given notice of the application.

Search orders are always made without notice. A supervising solicitor (independent of the applicant's firm) must be present at execution. The respondent has the right to seek legal advice before permitting entry, subject to a short time limit. A detailed record of items taken must be made.

Strike Out.answer:
Under CPR 3.4(2), a statement of case may be struck out where:
(1) It discloses no reasonable grounds for bringing or defending the claim;
(2) It is an abuse of the court's process or is otherwise likely to obstruct the just disposal of the proceedings;
(3) There has been a failure to comply with a rule, practice direction, or court order.

On ground (1), the court takes the pleaded facts at their highest — the question is whether, assuming all the facts are true, the pleading discloses a legally recognisable claim or defence. Evidence is not considered. The test is purely on the pleadings.

⚠️ Link — Summary judgment (see FLK1-DR-037): strike out tests the legal sufficiency of the pleadings; summary judgment tests whether the claim/defence has a real prospect of success on the evidence.

Formal Requirements.answer:
Under CPR 36.5, a Part 36 offer must:
(1) Be in writing;
(2) State that it is made pursuant to Part 36;
(3) Specify a period of not less than 21 days within which the defendant will be liable for the claimant's costs if the offer is accepted (the 'relevant period');
(4) State whether it relates to the whole claim, part of it, or an issue in the claim;
(5) State whether it takes into account any counterclaim.

A Part 36 offer is made 'without prejudice save as to costs' — it cannot be communicated to the trial judge until the question of costs arises after judgment.

An offer that does not comply with CPR 36.5 is not a valid Part 36 offer, but may still be a relevant offer under the court's general costs discretion (CPR 44.2).

Costs Consequences.answer:
Under CPR 36.17(4), where judgment is at least as advantageous to the claimant as their own Part 36 offer, the court will, unless unjust, order:
(1) Interest on any damages at up to 10% above base rate for some or all of the period from the expiry of the relevant period;
(2) Costs on the indemnity basis from the date of expiry of the relevant period;
(3) Interest on those costs at up to 10% above base rate;
(4) An additional amount of 10% of the first £500,000 awarded, and 5% of any amount above £500,000, subject to a maximum of £75,000.

⚠️ All four consequences apply cumulatively. The 10% additional amount cap is £75,000 — this is frequently tested in calculation scenarios.

⚠️ Link — Defendant's Part 36 offer consequences (see FLK1-DR-040): the asymmetry between CPR 36.17(3) and 36.17(4) is a core exam trap.

Trial Procedure.answer:
The usual order at a civil trial is:
(1) Claimant's opening speech (defendant may also open in complex cases);
(2) Claimant calls witnesses: witness statement stands as examination-in-chief; cross-examination by defendant; re-examination by claimant on matters arising in cross-examination only;
(3) Defendant calls witnesses in the same order;
(4) Expert evidence (if separate experts are called);
(5) Defendant's closing speech;
(6) Claimant's closing speech.

Note: in fast track trials, opening speeches are often dispensed with. Re-examination is strictly limited to matters arising from cross-examination — it cannot introduce new topics.

Overview & Methods.answer:
The principal methods are:
(1) Warrant of control: a County Court Bailiff or High Court Enforcement Officer (HCEO) seizes and sells the debtor's goods;
(2) Third party debt order (CPR 72): money owed to the judgment debtor by a third party (e.g. a bank) is paid directly to the creditor;
(3) Charging order (Charging Orders Act 1979): a charge is placed on the debtor's property, enforced by an application for sale;
(4) Attachment of earnings (Attachment of Earnings Act 1971): the debtor's employer pays a portion of their wages to the creditor;
(5) Insolvency proceedings: statutory demand followed by bankruptcy (individuals) or winding-up petition (companies).

